just general and broad?

00:18:57.620 --> 00:19:00.190 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: There are so
many poltergeist cases.

00:19:00.190 --> 00:19:03.710 align:middle line:84%
Really quite a
specialized study could

00:19:03.710 --> 00:19:06.700 align:middle line:84%
be made of just that particular
phenomenon, because there

00:19:06.700 --> 00:19:07.974 align:middle line:90%
are so many cases.

00:19:07.974 --> 00:19:09.140 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They're everywhere.

00:19:09.140 --> 00:19:11.940 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: They're everywhere--
the Columbus poltergeist

00:19:11.940 --> 00:19:14.430 align:middle line:84%
with Tina Resch. there's
the "Conjuring 2"

00:19:14.430 --> 00:19:20.130 align:middle line:84%
movie now that's taken an
old case and rehashed it.

00:19:20.130 --> 00:19:23.440 align:middle line:84%
But what you typically
have with a poltergeist--

00:19:23.440 --> 00:19:27.330 align:middle line:84%
and remember the boy R behind
"The Exorcist" started really

00:19:27.330 --> 00:19:30.950 align:middle line:84%
as a poltergeist case-- you
have a kid, or sometimes

00:19:30.950 --> 00:19:33.440 align:middle line:84%
a couple of
children, in a house,

00:19:33.440 --> 00:19:35.770 align:middle line:90%
and things begin to happen.

00:19:35.770 --> 00:19:39.510 align:middle line:84%
Objects are thrown
about, people are amazed.

00:19:39.510 --> 00:19:42.750 align:middle line:84%
And what's happening is
that parents are usually

00:19:42.750 --> 00:19:45.280 align:middle line:90%
quite credulous.

00:19:45.280 --> 00:19:48.030 align:middle line:84%
Parents who say, OK,
Jimmy, that's enough,

00:19:48.030 --> 00:19:51.750 align:middle line:84%
I'll slap you around if you
do that again, those cases we

00:19:51.750 --> 00:19:53.520 align:middle line:90%
never hear about.

00:19:53.520 --> 00:19:57.310 align:middle line:84%
But when skeptics try to come
in and use their knowledge

00:19:57.310 --> 00:19:59.370 align:middle line:84%
to explain what's
happening, the parents

00:19:59.370 --> 00:20:01.210 align:middle line:90%
are protective of the children.

00:20:01.210 --> 00:20:05.490 align:middle line:84%
And skeptics rarely ever get on
the premises-- very few cases.

00:20:05.490 --> 00:20:07.490 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But that's not
to say that these cases,

00:20:07.490 --> 00:20:10.390 align:middle line:84%
these poltergeists cases,
aren't real, right?

00:20:10.390 --> 00:20:13.280 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Well,
there's real mischief,

00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:16.870 align:middle line:84%
but there's no scientific
evidence for anything

00:20:16.870 --> 00:20:18.040 align:middle line:90%
called a poltergeist.

00:20:18.040 --> 00:20:21.725 align:middle line:84%
What happens is that time and
again, the kids are caught.

00:20:21.725 --> 00:20:23.910 align:middle line:90%
They're first suspected.

00:20:23.910 --> 00:20:27.860 align:middle line:84%
Eventually-- Tina
Resch was caught.

00:20:27.860 --> 00:20:31.900 align:middle line:84%
The little girl in "The
Conjuring 2" movie was caught.

00:20:31.900 --> 00:20:34.540 align:middle line:84%
And again, in come the
defenders saying, well,

00:20:34.540 --> 00:20:38.390 align:middle line:84%
they may have gotten
caught up in the brouhaha,

00:20:38.390 --> 00:20:40.600 align:middle line:84%
but there's some
real material there.

00:20:40.600 --> 00:20:42.290 align:middle line:90%
They didn't fake everything.

00:20:42.290 --> 00:20:46.170 align:middle line:84%
Well, it looks like
perhaps that they did.

00:20:46.170 --> 00:20:48.960 align:middle line:84%
And people don't
understand what's going on.

00:20:48.960 --> 00:20:53.780 align:middle line:84%
They'll say, for example, having
no knowledge of magic tricks,

00:20:53.780 --> 00:20:57.050 align:middle line:84%
they'll say, well, the
person who is watching

00:20:57.050 --> 00:20:59.080 align:middle line:84%
was looking into
that other room,

00:20:59.080 --> 00:21:02.620 align:middle line:84%
and they see this object
jump off a shelf and break,

00:21:02.620 --> 00:21:05.010 align:middle line:84%
and little Jimmy was
nowhere in the room.

00:21:05.010 --> 00:21:06.540 align:middle line:90%
He was behind him.

00:21:06.540 --> 00:21:10.090 align:middle line:84%
What they don't realize is that
little Jimmy may have picked up

00:21:10.090 --> 00:21:15.170 align:middle line:84%
an object earlier, hidden it,
and tossed it over the guy's

00:21:15.170 --> 00:21:18.360 align:middle line:84%
shoulder, and then the
guy sees it in mid air,

00:21:18.360 --> 00:21:21.230 align:middle line:84%
and he's convinced because
it usually was on the shelf,

00:21:21.230 --> 00:21:23.220 align:middle line:84%
he's convinced he
saw it leap up.

00:21:23.220 --> 00:21:27.820 align:middle line:84%
People are just notoriously
bad witnesses for magic tricks,

00:21:27.820 --> 00:21:30.550 align:middle line:84%
whether they're done by
professional stage magician

00:21:30.550 --> 00:21:33.240 align:middle line:90%
or the amateur antics of a kid.

00:21:33.240 --> 00:21:36.990 align:middle line:84%
If you go through, as I've
done with many of these cases,

00:21:36.990 --> 00:21:39.305 align:middle line:84%
using just a
magician's knowledge

00:21:39.305 --> 00:21:40.430 align:middle line:90%
of how this could be done--

00:21:40.430 --> 00:21:41.560 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Knowledge
of trickery-- right.

00:21:41.560 --> 00:21:42.851 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: --I'm not impressed.

00:21:42.851 --> 00:21:45.860 align:middle line:84%
They've never found a
single poltergeist case

00:21:45.860 --> 00:21:47.930 align:middle line:84%
where I didn't think
that that could easily

00:21:47.930 --> 00:21:51.560 align:middle line:84%
be done as trickery or the
person who was insisting

00:21:51.560 --> 00:21:55.990 align:middle line:84%
on something was probably just
as mistaken as eyewitnesses

00:21:55.990 --> 00:22:00.230 align:middle line:84%
so often are in criminal
cases and in being witnesses

00:22:00.230 --> 00:22:01.260 align:middle line:90%
of Bigfoot.

00:22:01.260 --> 00:22:03.700 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now one of the great
haunting cases, of course

00:22:03.700 --> 00:22:08.401 align:middle line:84%
depicted again by Hollywood,
in "The Conjuring."

00:22:08.401 --> 00:22:10.950 align:middle line:84%
>>Give us a sign that you
want to communicate with us.

00:22:10.950 --> 00:22:16.926 align:middle line:90%


00:22:16.926 --> 00:22:17.922 align:middle line:90%
Nothing.

00:22:17.922 --> 00:22:19.914 align:middle line:90%
[CLOCK CHIMING]

00:22:19.914 --> 00:22:23.900 align:middle line:90%
[CHILDREN LAUGHING]

00:22:23.900 --> 00:22:24.850 align:middle line:90%
>>What are you guys?

00:22:24.850 --> 00:22:26.170 align:middle line:84%
>>Well, we've been
called ghost hunters,

00:22:26.170 --> 00:22:27.128 align:middle line:90%
paranormal researchers.

00:22:27.128 --> 00:22:29.000 align:middle line:84%
>>But we prefer
to be known simply

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:30.737 align:middle line:90%
as Ed and Lorraine Warren.

00:22:30.737 --> 00:22:35.525 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:22:35.525 --> 00:22:40.290 align:middle line:90%


00:22:40.290 --> 00:22:43.280 align:middle line:84%
>>There is someone here that
would like to talk to you.

00:22:43.280 --> 00:22:45.386 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:22:45.386 --> 00:22:47.510 align:middle line:84%
>>There's something horrible
happening in my house.

00:22:47.510 --> 00:22:50.486 align:middle line:90%
[CLOCK TICKING LOUDLY]

00:22:50.486 --> 00:22:51.974 align:middle line:90%


00:22:51.974 --> 00:22:52.966 align:middle line:90%
[CRASHING]

00:22:52.966 --> 00:22:53.958 align:middle line:90%
[GASPING]

00:22:53.958 --> 00:22:54.950 align:middle line:90%
[GLASS BREAKING]

00:22:54.950 --> 00:22:55.942 align:middle line:90%
[SCREAMING]

00:22:55.942 --> 00:22:56.742 align:middle line:90%
>>Kat?

00:22:56.742 --> 00:22:58.800 align:middle line:90%
>>It's November 1, 1971.

00:22:58.800 --> 00:23:01.590 align:middle line:84%
I am sitting here with Carolyn
Perron, who, with her family,

00:23:01.590 --> 00:23:03.810 align:middle line:84%
has been experiencing
supernatural occurrences.

00:23:03.810 --> 00:23:06.140 align:middle line:84%
>>You picking up
anything in here, hon?

00:23:06.140 --> 00:23:08.380 align:middle line:84%
>>Something awful
happened here, Ed.

00:23:08.380 --> 00:23:10.332 align:middle line:90%
>>What is it?

00:23:10.332 --> 00:23:12.260 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:23:12.260 --> 00:23:16.660 align:middle line:84%
Whatever Lorraine sees, feels,
touches takes a toll on her,

00:23:16.660 --> 00:23:18.730 align:middle line:90%
a little piece each time.

00:23:18.730 --> 00:23:19.640 align:middle line:90%
[THUD]

00:23:19.640 --> 00:23:21.835 align:middle line:84%
>>You have a lot
of spirits in here.

00:23:21.835 --> 00:23:23.990 align:middle line:84%
But there's one that
I'm most worried about,

00:23:23.990 --> 00:23:25.507 align:middle line:90%
because it is so hateful.

00:23:25.507 --> 00:23:28.692 align:middle line:90%


00:23:28.692 --> 00:23:31.590 align:middle line:84%
>>(WHISPERING) Look
what she made me do.

00:23:31.590 --> 00:23:35.454 align:middle line:90%
[SOBBING]

00:23:35.454 --> 00:23:37.386 align:middle line:90%
[SCREAMING]

00:23:37.386 --> 00:23:38.630 align:middle line:90%
>>We have to get out of here.

00:23:38.630 --> 00:23:39.630 align:middle line:90%
>>That's not gonna help.

00:23:39.630 --> 00:23:41.900 align:middle line:84%
>>This thing has latched
itself to your family.

00:23:41.900 --> 00:23:43.124 align:middle line:90%
[SCREAMING]

00:23:43.124 --> 00:23:44.426 align:middle line:90%
[GLASS BREAKING]

00:23:44.426 --> 00:23:46.588 align:middle line:84%
>>Father, we never
seen nothing like this.

00:23:46.588 --> 00:23:47.388 align:middle line:90%
[GLASS BREAKING]

00:23:47.388 --> 00:23:48.188 align:middle line:90%
[SCREAMING]

00:23:48.188 --> 00:23:49.424 align:middle line:90%
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

00:23:49.424 --> 00:23:50.340 align:middle line:90%
>>I'm coming with you.

00:23:50.340 --> 00:23:50.740 align:middle line:90%
>>No way.

00:23:50.740 --> 00:23:51.660 align:middle line:90%
I can't lose you.

00:23:51.660 --> 00:23:52.147 align:middle line:90%
[WOOD CRACKING]

00:23:52.147 --> 00:23:53.121 align:middle line:90%
[SCREAMING]

00:23:53.121 --> 00:23:54.989 align:middle line:90%
>>Lorraine?

00:23:54.989 --> 00:23:56.530 align:middle line:84%
>>There's a lady in
a dirty nightgown

00:23:56.530 --> 00:23:58.478 align:middle line:90%
that I see in my dreams.

00:23:58.478 --> 00:24:00.913 align:middle line:84%
She's standing in
front of my mom's bed.

00:24:00.913 --> 00:24:03.348 align:middle line:90%
[SCREAMING]

00:24:03.348 --> 00:24:05.296 align:middle line:90%
[ROARING]

00:24:05.296 --> 00:24:10.459 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:24:10.459 --> 00:24:11.500 align:middle line:90%
>>Do you want to see him?

00:24:11.500 --> 00:24:12.300 align:middle line:90%
>>Yeah.

00:24:12.300 --> 00:24:14.000 align:middle line:84%
>>When the music
stops, you'll see him

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:16.000 align:middle line:84%
in the mirror
standing behind you.

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:19.206 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC BOX MUSIC PLAYING]

00:24:19.206 --> 00:24:23.386 align:middle line:84%
>>(WHISPERING) Look
what she made me do.

00:24:23.386 --> 00:24:25.750 align:middle line:90%
[SCREAMING]

00:24:25.750 --> 00:24:29.340 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: OK, now what about
this case, Joe, "The Conjuring?"

00:24:29.340 --> 00:24:31.050 align:middle line:10%
>>NICKELL: I've had
the good fortune

00:24:31.050 --> 00:24:33.500 align:middle line:10%
of being at the
very house that was

00:24:33.500 --> 00:24:37.600 align:middle line:10%
at the center of
this decade of claims

00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:41.450 align:middle line:10%
by the Perron family
of demonic forces.

00:24:41.450 --> 00:24:46.800 align:middle line:84%
Ed and Lorraine Warren,
who made sort of a career

00:24:46.800 --> 00:24:51.516 align:middle line:84%
out of claiming to be a
demonologist and a clairvoyant.

00:24:51.516 --> 00:24:52.890 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Ed is no
longer with us.

00:24:52.890 --> 00:24:54.480 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Ed is
no longer with us.

00:24:54.480 --> 00:24:56.970 align:middle line:84%
They've taken
hapless families that

00:24:56.970 --> 00:24:59.960 align:middle line:84%
have had some trouble,
poltergeist or call it

00:24:59.960 --> 00:25:03.820 align:middle line:84%
what you will, and have managed
to convince people that this

00:25:03.820 --> 00:25:06.580 align:middle line:90%
was really something demonic.

00:25:06.580 --> 00:25:09.820 align:middle line:84%
And pretty soon, a book or
movie deal was in the offering.

00:25:09.820 --> 00:25:12.150 align:middle line:84%
And they did this from
Amityville, a haunting

00:25:12.150 --> 00:25:13.850 align:middle line:90%
in Connecticut.

00:25:13.850 --> 00:25:15.890 align:middle line:84%
There are just case
after case after case.

00:25:15.890 --> 00:25:17.940 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: There's another
one about a doll called

00:25:17.940 --> 00:25:20.200 align:middle line:90%
Annabel, right?

00:25:20.200 --> 00:25:21.840 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: In many
of these cases,

00:25:21.840 --> 00:25:24.870 align:middle line:84%
the co-authors of the
books have now come forward

00:25:24.870 --> 00:25:28.070 align:middle line:84%
and said, well, Ed suggested
they kind of exaggerate

00:25:28.070 --> 00:25:30.650 align:middle line:90%
and make it scary.

00:25:30.650 --> 00:25:33.180 align:middle line:84%
But I've had the
good fortune recently

00:25:33.180 --> 00:25:38.100 align:middle line:84%
to have spent a week
driving to Rhode Island,

00:25:38.100 --> 00:25:42.720 align:middle line:84%
invited by the couple that
lives in that house now

00:25:42.720 --> 00:25:45.200 align:middle line:90%
and has done so for 30 years.

00:25:45.200 --> 00:25:47.140 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And everything
is cool, right?

00:25:47.140 --> 00:25:48.140 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: Nothing much.

00:25:48.140 --> 00:25:48.990 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: No issues.

00:25:48.990 --> 00:25:52.090 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Well,
like everybody else,

00:25:52.090 --> 00:25:55.100 align:middle line:84%
living in an old house they
occasionally hear a noise.

00:25:55.100 --> 00:25:56.250 align:middle line:90%
Maybe they weren't sure.

00:25:56.250 --> 00:25:58.340 align:middle line:84%
Pretty quickly they
figured out, we

00:25:58.340 --> 00:25:59.920 align:middle line:90%
don't have demons in the house.

00:25:59.920 --> 00:26:03.450 align:middle line:84%
What we have are some
noises, some odd things.

00:26:03.450 --> 00:26:06.170 align:middle line:84%
Norma Sutcliffe showed
me, for example--

00:26:06.170 --> 00:26:13.710 align:middle line:84%
and this is big in the book
that Andrea Perron wrote.

00:26:13.710 --> 00:26:17.790 align:middle line:84%
She wrote a trilogy of books,
the most voluminous bunch

00:26:17.790 --> 00:26:22.860 align:middle line:84%
of repetitious gobbledygook I've
known about in the paranormal.

00:26:22.860 --> 00:26:24.530 align:middle line:84%
It would have been
a much better work

00:26:24.530 --> 00:26:28.240 align:middle line:84%
if she had stuck to one
volume and slimmed it down.

00:26:28.240 --> 00:26:30.240 align:middle line:84%
But they claim
that, for example,

00:26:30.240 --> 00:26:34.490 align:middle line:84%
that if you slept at night,
the cellar door-- and they

00:26:34.490 --> 00:26:37.990 align:middle line:84%
make the cellar sound
like this sinister place.

00:26:37.990 --> 00:26:40.390 align:middle line:84%
It's just a scary
old dank cellar

00:26:40.390 --> 00:26:42.590 align:middle line:90%
from an 18th century home.

00:26:42.590 --> 00:26:47.080 align:middle line:84%
But they've said that the
door would mysteriously

00:26:47.080 --> 00:26:48.652 align:middle line:84%
open about the same
time every night.

00:26:48.652 --> 00:26:49.860 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: [IMITATES SQUEAKING]

00:26:49.860 --> 00:26:52.820 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Or
sometimes you walk by,

00:26:52.820 --> 00:26:54.590 align:middle line:90%
and it would open behind you.

00:26:54.590 --> 00:26:58.370 align:middle line:84%
Well, Norma and her
husband figured this out.

00:26:58.370 --> 00:27:01.140 align:middle line:84%
What was happening was the
door was slightly warped.

00:27:01.140 --> 00:27:03.210 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It was
opening, though, right?

00:27:03.210 --> 00:27:05.100 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Well, it
would be latched.

00:27:05.100 --> 00:27:06.160 align:middle line:90%
It would be latched.

00:27:06.160 --> 00:27:08.320 align:middle line:84%
And then it would
open by itself.

00:27:08.320 --> 00:27:09.779 align:middle line:90%
So that was the big mystery.

00:27:09.779 --> 00:27:11.070 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: There's a ghost there!

00:27:11.070 --> 00:27:14.560 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: What was happening
is the door was slightly warped.

00:27:14.560 --> 00:27:17.950 align:middle line:84%
And the catch would catch
enough to hold it in place,

00:27:17.950 --> 00:27:20.940 align:middle line:90%
but it wasn't fully engaged.

00:27:20.940 --> 00:27:23.040 align:middle line:84%
And of course at
night, the house

00:27:23.040 --> 00:27:26.890 align:middle line:84%
cools, things settle,
you hear noises.

00:27:26.890 --> 00:27:29.460 align:middle line:84%
Temperatures are
having an effect.

00:27:29.460 --> 00:27:33.060 align:middle line:84%
And the latch would
cool and pop open.

00:27:33.060 --> 00:27:36.490 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes if you walked
by it, what would happen

00:27:36.490 --> 00:27:39.410 align:middle line:84%
is you would step on a loose
floorboard right in front

00:27:39.410 --> 00:27:41.730 align:middle line:84%
of the door, and the
door would move a little,

00:27:41.730 --> 00:27:44.380 align:middle line:84%
and the latch would
pop open again.

00:27:44.380 --> 00:27:46.790 align:middle line:84%
So they just simply
had the door fixed.

00:27:46.790 --> 00:27:48.296 align:middle line:90%
And it doesn't do that anymore.

00:27:48.296 --> 00:27:48.642 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It stopped.

00:27:48.642 --> 00:27:48.990 align:middle line:90%
Ah.

00:27:48.990 --> 00:27:50.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Norma took
me through the house,

00:27:50.870 --> 00:27:54.690 align:middle line:84%
and we looked at
things like that.

00:27:54.690 --> 00:27:58.630 align:middle line:84%
And what I found, and I
had done a lot of my work

00:27:58.630 --> 00:28:02.760 align:middle line:84%
from analyzing the
accounts, as I always do,

00:28:02.760 --> 00:28:08.550 align:middle line:84%
those stories-- and I know that
some things sincerely happened

00:28:08.550 --> 00:28:11.196 align:middle line:84%
to some of the family members,
but look what you had.

00:28:11.196 --> 00:28:16.040 align:middle line:84%
You had a sort of New
Agey mother and five girls

00:28:16.040 --> 00:28:20.190 align:middle line:84%
and a father who was largely
absent due to his work.

00:28:20.190 --> 00:28:23.080 align:middle line:84%
And the kids were all
looking to compete

00:28:23.080 --> 00:28:25.700 align:middle line:84%
for their mother's attention
or for father's attention.

00:28:25.700 --> 00:28:27.630 align:middle line:84%
They were trying to
outdo each other.

00:28:27.630 --> 00:28:30.140 align:middle line:84%
You had a little bit
of mischief, I think.

00:28:30.140 --> 00:28:33.560 align:middle line:84%
I would call it "poltergeists"
in quotation marks.

00:28:33.560 --> 00:28:38.190 align:middle line:84%
You had, as you often
have, somebody wakes up,

00:28:38.190 --> 00:28:42.059 align:middle line:84%
and they see some sinister
figure, having just woken.

00:28:42.059 --> 00:28:43.350 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: A shadow or something.

00:28:43.350 --> 00:28:45.487 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: And they're
unable to move.

00:28:45.487 --> 00:28:46.820 align:middle line:90%
And this is a common phenomenon.

00:28:46.820 --> 00:28:47.500 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's sleep paralysis.

00:28:47.500 --> 00:28:48.320 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: Yeah.

00:28:48.320 --> 00:28:51.140 align:middle line:84%
It's a waking dream
with sleep paralysis.

00:28:51.140 --> 00:28:52.980 align:middle line:90%
It's understood very, very well.

00:28:52.980 --> 00:28:55.620 align:middle line:84%
And you can go through the
book and just check off

00:28:55.620 --> 00:28:58.932 align:middle line:84%
the incidents in which that
is just described perfectly

00:28:58.932 --> 00:29:00.390 align:middle line:84%
and must have been
the explanation.

00:29:00.390 --> 00:29:03.620 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It sounds to me,
Joe, that you do not believe

00:29:03.620 --> 00:29:06.530 align:middle line:90%
in ghosts based on this.

00:29:06.530 --> 00:29:08.380 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: I'm not in
the belief business.

00:29:08.380 --> 00:29:11.400 align:middle line:84%
I'm in the
investigative business.

00:29:11.400 --> 00:29:14.840 align:middle line:84%
And I've not seen any
evidence that I believe--

00:29:14.840 --> 00:29:15.640 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yes.

00:29:15.640 --> 00:29:18.960 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: --warrented-- right,
yet-- that warranted belief

00:29:18.960 --> 00:29:20.430 align:middle line:90%
in ghosts.

00:29:20.430 --> 00:29:24.100 align:middle line:84%
Ghosts are really not
a very scientific idea.

00:29:24.100 --> 00:29:27.630 align:middle line:84%
The idea that yes, we might have
some life energy that science

00:29:27.630 --> 00:29:31.610 align:middle line:84%
can't quite find, but the
idea that some form of energy

00:29:31.610 --> 00:29:36.440 align:middle line:84%
leaves the body at death and
doesn't dissipate and continues

00:29:36.440 --> 00:29:40.360 align:middle line:84%
after the source is gone
and continues for 100 years

00:29:40.360 --> 00:29:42.060 align:middle line:90%
is scientific nonsense.

00:29:42.060 --> 00:29:45.370 align:middle line:84%
It's like thinking that that
light bulb somehow when you

00:29:45.370 --> 00:29:48.450 align:middle line:84%
turn the light off goes
to another dimension.

00:29:48.450 --> 00:29:52.280 align:middle line:84%
No, it just turns into
heat energy and dissipates.

00:29:52.280 --> 00:29:55.630 align:middle line:84%
The idea that a
ghost without a brain

00:29:55.630 --> 00:29:58.630 align:middle line:84%
would be able to walk,
talk, and say boo

00:29:58.630 --> 00:30:00.190 align:middle line:90%
is not a scientific idea.

00:30:00.190 --> 00:30:02.495 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do you believe
in life after death?

00:30:02.495 --> 00:30:05.790 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: I'm not in the
belief business, George.

00:30:05.790 --> 00:30:07.360 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I'm gonna get you yet.

00:30:07.360 --> 00:30:08.660 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: I don't believe--

00:30:08.660 --> 00:30:11.400 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So what happens when
you die, in your opinion.

00:30:11.400 --> 00:30:12.200 align:middle line:90%
You don't know.

00:30:12.200 --> 00:30:14.000 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: Everything stops.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:15.020 align:middle line:90%
I think it must stop.

00:30:15.020 --> 00:30:15.820 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's it.

00:30:15.820 --> 00:30:15.860 align:middle line:90%
Done.

00:30:15.860 --> 00:30:17.860 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Because we are
brain-centered beings.

00:30:17.860 --> 00:30:20.300 align:middle line:84%
I've dwelled on this a
lot in my own thinking.

00:30:20.300 --> 00:30:21.810 align:middle line:90%
I'm a serious poet.

00:30:21.810 --> 00:30:25.900 align:middle line:84%
I would love to imagine
other worlds and so forth.

00:30:25.900 --> 00:30:33.140 align:middle line:84%
But in fact, when our brain
is injured or not doing well,

00:30:33.140 --> 00:30:34.890 align:middle line:90%
things happen to it.

00:30:34.890 --> 00:30:40.520 align:middle line:84%
If the brain malfunctions,
then there are consequences.

00:30:40.520 --> 00:30:45.120 align:middle line:84%
My mother had Alzheimer's, and
I watched the effects of that.

00:30:45.120 --> 00:30:47.970 align:middle line:84%
To believe in ghosts
is almost to say, oh,

00:30:47.970 --> 00:30:49.230 align:middle line:90%
you don't really need a brain.

00:30:49.230 --> 00:30:50.560 align:middle line:90%
We don't need a brain.

00:30:50.560 --> 00:30:54.200 align:middle line:84%
You just have this spirit, and
it has a sort of spirit brain,

00:30:54.200 --> 00:30:56.690 align:middle line:84%
and the real brain
doesn't have-- no, that's

00:30:56.690 --> 00:30:57.490 align:middle line:90%
just nonsense.

00:30:57.490 --> 00:30:59.100 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Joe, have
you investigated

00:30:59.100 --> 00:31:02.630 align:middle line:84%
anything-- anything--
that would lead

00:31:02.630 --> 00:31:06.020 align:middle line:84%
you to believe that maybe
there's some credence to some

00:31:06.020 --> 00:31:07.840 align:middle line:90%
of the supernatural stuff.

00:31:07.840 --> 00:31:09.010 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: I have not.

00:31:09.010 --> 00:31:09.380 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Nothing.

00:31:09.380 --> 00:31:12.110 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: And that doesn't mean
that I can explain everything.

00:31:12.110 --> 00:31:14.170 align:middle line:84%
People always ask me,
is there anything you

00:31:14.170 --> 00:31:15.650 align:middle line:90%
haven't been able to explain?

00:31:15.650 --> 00:31:16.790 align:middle line:90%
Well, lots of things.

00:31:16.790 --> 00:31:17.767 align:middle line:90%
And then they say, see?

00:31:17.767 --> 00:31:18.930 align:middle line:90%
See?

00:31:18.930 --> 00:31:20.390 align:middle line:90%
As if they've got me.

00:31:20.390 --> 00:31:22.910 align:middle line:84%
No, because the
rest of that answer

00:31:22.910 --> 00:31:27.960 align:middle line:84%
is I haven't
examined things where

00:31:27.960 --> 00:31:31.790 align:middle line:84%
there is no evidence, where
people or their stories

00:31:31.790 --> 00:31:35.240 align:middle line:84%
long ago, far away, not
very investigatable.

00:31:35.240 --> 00:31:37.580 align:middle line:84%
I have no idea what
happened in those cases,

00:31:37.580 --> 00:31:39.790 align:middle line:84%
because we really don't
have any evidence.

00:31:39.790 --> 00:31:43.520 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Would you like some
of these stories to be true?

00:31:43.520 --> 00:31:45.970 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Like everybody
else, like everyone,

00:31:45.970 --> 00:31:48.830 align:middle line:84%
I think we are
hopeful human beings.

00:31:48.830 --> 00:31:51.690 align:middle line:84%
We want to believe
in wonderful things.

00:31:51.690 --> 00:31:54.910 align:middle line:84%
If we were voting, we would
raise our hands right now.

00:31:54.910 --> 00:31:56.030 align:middle line:90%
Are ghosts real?

00:31:56.030 --> 00:32:00.570 align:middle line:84%
Sure, because we would
vote for that because we

00:32:00.570 --> 00:32:03.300 align:middle line:90%
want to live on after we die.

00:32:03.300 --> 00:32:05.040 align:middle line:90%
Almost everybody wants that.

00:32:05.040 --> 00:32:07.130 align:middle line:84%
Or we want to believe
that extraterrestrials

00:32:07.130 --> 00:32:10.320 align:middle line:84%
are real because we don't want
to be alone in the universe.

00:32:10.320 --> 00:32:12.400 align:middle line:90%
These are all wonderful ideas.

00:32:12.400 --> 00:32:16.270 align:middle line:84%
It's just that the
evidence is not there yet.

00:32:16.270 --> 00:32:20.210 align:middle line:84%
I suspect it's going to be a
long time coming and possibly

00:32:20.210 --> 00:32:21.010 align:middle line:90%
never.

00:32:21.010 --> 00:32:22.260 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What about faith?

00:32:22.260 --> 00:32:23.510 align:middle line:90%
Where does faith fit in?

00:32:23.510 --> 00:32:24.310 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: Faith?

00:32:24.310 --> 00:32:25.310 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yes.

00:32:25.310 --> 00:32:29.940 align:middle line:84%
Let me give you an
example, a miracle story.

00:32:29.940 --> 00:32:35.670 align:middle line:84%
A lady goes into her garage
and sees her son hanging

00:32:35.670 --> 00:32:37.080 align:middle line:90%
from a rope.

00:32:37.080 --> 00:32:39.590 align:middle line:90%
He attempted suicide.

00:32:39.590 --> 00:32:43.110 align:middle line:84%
She gets there with enough
time that he's still alive.

00:32:43.110 --> 00:32:45.490 align:middle line:90%
But what is she going to do?

00:32:45.490 --> 00:32:48.030 align:middle line:90%
The guy weighs 200 pounds.

00:32:48.030 --> 00:32:51.070 align:middle line:90%
She's 110.

00:32:51.070 --> 00:32:54.812 align:middle line:90%
She screams for help from God.

00:32:54.812 --> 00:32:59.670 align:middle line:84%
Out of nowhere,
she says, she sees

00:32:59.670 --> 00:33:04.700 align:middle line:84%
like an angel or
hands joining her,

00:33:04.700 --> 00:33:09.740 align:middle line:84%
lifting this 200-pound guy
up to release the stress

00:33:09.740 --> 00:33:12.210 align:middle line:90%
and the tension on the rope.

00:33:12.210 --> 00:33:15.550 align:middle line:84%
And as she screams,
a neighbor comes by

00:33:15.550 --> 00:33:17.520 align:middle line:90%
and helps and gets him down.

00:33:17.520 --> 00:33:19.610 align:middle line:90%
The guy lives.

00:33:19.610 --> 00:33:21.630 align:middle line:90%
How do you explain that?

00:33:21.630 --> 00:33:23.762 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: First of all,
we skeptics have a saying.

00:33:23.762 --> 00:33:25.220 align:middle line:84%
Before we try to
explain something,

00:33:25.220 --> 00:33:28.270 align:middle line:84%
we have to make sure it really,
really happened as described.

00:33:28.270 --> 00:33:32.524 align:middle line:84%
I take you that you've seen
a case somewhat like that.

00:33:32.524 --> 00:33:33.940 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We have
to assume it did.

00:33:33.940 --> 00:33:37.160 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: But we can certainly
imagine a situation like that.

00:33:37.160 --> 00:33:39.720 align:middle line:90%
It's reasonably credible.

00:33:39.720 --> 00:33:43.650 align:middle line:84%
We're all able to summon
a great deal of strength

00:33:43.650 --> 00:33:45.410 align:middle line:90%
when we really need to.

00:33:45.410 --> 00:33:46.910 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Adrenalin rush.

00:33:46.910 --> 00:33:47.710 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: Yeah.

00:33:47.710 --> 00:33:49.960 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:33:49.960 --> 00:33:52.240 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Like lifting a car
when it falls on somebody.

00:33:52.240 --> 00:33:53.990 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: We're able
to empower ourselves

00:33:53.990 --> 00:33:56.310 align:middle line:84%
in ways that are really
impressive, and good that we

00:33:56.310 --> 00:33:57.560 align:middle line:90%
are.

00:33:57.560 --> 00:34:01.970 align:middle line:84%
But what happens
with miracle claims,

00:34:01.970 --> 00:34:05.670 align:middle line:84%
miracle claims
invariably are based

00:34:05.670 --> 00:34:08.571 align:middle line:84%
on what's called an
argument from ignorance.

00:34:08.571 --> 00:34:12.860 align:middle line:84%
The miracles are not
from positive evidence.

00:34:12.860 --> 00:34:15.590 align:middle line:90%
They're from negative evidence.

00:34:15.590 --> 00:34:18.610 align:middle line:84%
Every miracle claim-- look
at a bunch of them-- weeping

00:34:18.610 --> 00:34:22.449 align:middle line:84%
statues, faith healing,
are all based on, well,

00:34:22.449 --> 00:34:24.370 align:middle line:84%
we don't know how that
could have happened.

00:34:24.370 --> 00:34:27.260 align:middle line:84%
The doctors say they don't know
why Mrs. Smith's cancer went

00:34:27.260 --> 00:34:28.300 align:middle line:90%
into remission.

00:34:28.300 --> 00:34:30.890 align:middle line:84%
It must be a miracle of
the Holy Virgin Mary.

00:34:30.890 --> 00:34:31.690 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:34:31.690 --> 00:34:34.573 align:middle line:84%
When you say we don't know,
or doctors don't know,

00:34:34.573 --> 00:34:36.550 align:middle line:90%
that's where you stop.

00:34:36.550 --> 00:34:39.980 align:middle line:84%
You don't say, therefore,
it's a miracle.

00:34:39.980 --> 00:34:43.670 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, the medical
bureau at Lourdes,

00:34:43.670 --> 00:34:46.920 align:middle line:84%
the famous healing shrine,
said a few years ago

00:34:46.920 --> 00:34:49.300 align:middle line:84%
they were going to
quit playing that game.

00:34:49.300 --> 00:34:50.949 align:middle line:84%
Because they were
willing to say,

00:34:50.949 --> 00:34:53.454 align:middle line:90%
OK, some cases are remarkable.

00:34:53.454 --> 00:34:54.620 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Something happened.

00:34:54.620 --> 00:34:55.030 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:34:55.030 --> 00:34:56.420 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: They would say that.

00:34:56.420 --> 00:34:58.350 align:middle line:84%
They're not going to
use the word "miracle."

00:34:58.350 --> 00:35:00.210 align:middle line:84%
Because what's
happening is the people

00:35:00.210 --> 00:35:02.510 align:middle line:84%
who are wanting to
sell you a miracle

00:35:02.510 --> 00:35:04.420 align:middle line:90%
are trying to trump science.

00:35:04.420 --> 00:35:06.570 align:middle line:84%
They're trying to
say, oh, yeah, sure.

00:35:06.570 --> 00:35:09.650 align:middle line:84%
Mrs. Smith may have had some
chemotherapy treatments,

00:35:09.650 --> 00:35:11.510 align:middle line:84%
but the doctors aren't
sure that was enough.

00:35:11.510 --> 00:35:12.801 align:middle line:90%
There had to be something more.

00:35:12.801 --> 00:35:15.950 align:middle line:84%
They're wanting to sell you
something more, a mystery,

00:35:15.950 --> 00:35:18.370 align:middle line:84%
and convince you that
there's a supernatural.

00:35:18.370 --> 00:35:19.786 align:middle line:84%
And there are
people who are going

00:35:19.786 --> 00:35:21.980 align:middle line:84%
to be in business to sell
you the supernatural.

00:35:21.980 --> 00:35:25.970 align:middle line:84%
So what we have to do is
look for evidence everywhere

00:35:25.970 --> 00:35:31.100 align:middle line:84%
in every area, in
every miracle case.

00:35:31.100 --> 00:35:35.050 align:middle line:84%
We have to look at it and
say, what do we really know,

00:35:35.050 --> 00:35:36.360 align:middle line:90%
and where's the evidence?

00:35:36.360 --> 00:35:40.530 align:middle line:84%
And I've just not seen-- I've
seen a lot of miracle hoaxes.

00:35:40.530 --> 00:35:42.810 align:middle line:84%
I've seen a lot of
wishful thinking.

00:35:42.810 --> 00:35:45.760 align:middle line:84%
But I have not seen
anything I thought

00:35:45.760 --> 00:35:48.090 align:middle line:90%
it was probably supernatural.

00:35:48.090 --> 00:35:49.950 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Our friend
Erich von Daniken

00:35:49.950 --> 00:35:52.250 align:middle line:84%
wrote the book called
"Chariots of the Gods."

00:35:52.250 --> 00:35:55.070 align:middle line:84%
And he is convinced
that we have been

00:35:55.070 --> 00:35:58.750 align:middle line:84%
visited from
extraterrestrials from above.

00:35:58.750 --> 00:36:03.560 align:middle line:84%
One of the things that he uses
as his source to believe this

00:36:03.560 --> 00:36:07.810 align:middle line:84%
are the Nazca Lines in Peru,
where only from the air can

00:36:07.810 --> 00:36:11.050 align:middle line:84%
you figure out what the heck
you're looking at-- monkeys,

00:36:11.050 --> 00:36:13.140 align:middle line:90%
spiders, things like that.

00:36:13.140 --> 00:36:15.560 align:middle line:84%
You really can't make it out
when you're walking around

00:36:15.560 --> 00:36:17.059 align:middle line:90%
on good old planet Earth.

00:36:17.059 --> 00:36:18.350 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: They are remarkable.

00:36:18.350 --> 00:36:19.200 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What do
you think of that?

00:36:19.200 --> 00:36:20.900 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Those
figures are remarkable.

00:36:20.900 --> 00:36:24.450 align:middle line:84%
And what I resent about von
Daniken is that he, over

00:36:24.450 --> 00:36:26.590 align:middle line:84%
and over, whether it's the
building of the pyramids

00:36:26.590 --> 00:36:29.920 align:middle line:84%
or the stone statues on Easter
Island or what have you,

00:36:29.920 --> 00:36:33.670 align:middle line:84%
there's a kind of implied
racism in von Daniken's stuff,

00:36:33.670 --> 00:36:36.650 align:middle line:84%
that ancient, nonwhite
people couldn't

00:36:36.650 --> 00:36:39.430 align:middle line:84%
have done this because,
well, they're nonwhite.

00:36:39.430 --> 00:36:42.780 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's there,
not expressly stated,

00:36:42.780 --> 00:36:45.940 align:middle line:84%
but it's implicit in
all of his writings,

00:36:45.940 --> 00:36:49.260 align:middle line:84%
that somehow they needed
higher beings to help them.

00:36:49.260 --> 00:36:52.720 align:middle line:84%
And I think it demeans
the great accomplishments

00:36:52.720 --> 00:36:54.252 align:middle line:84%
of the people who
built these things

00:36:54.252 --> 00:36:55.460 align:middle line:90%
and who created these things.

00:36:55.460 --> 00:36:59.840 align:middle line:84%
And I think the Nazca lines
are remarkable and were created

00:36:59.840 --> 00:37:02.840 align:middle line:84%
by the Nazca people who
flourished in the years

00:37:02.840 --> 00:37:07.240 align:middle line:84%
before and after Jesus
over a long period of time.

00:37:07.240 --> 00:37:10.570 align:middle line:84%
What I tried to do, my
little contribution to that,

00:37:10.570 --> 00:37:12.650 align:middle line:84%
was that people were
saying that there

00:37:12.650 --> 00:37:17.240 align:middle line:84%
was no way those ancient peoples
could have made a drawing so

00:37:17.240 --> 00:37:21.080 align:middle line:84%
large that you can only
see it from an airplane

00:37:21.080 --> 00:37:23.190 align:middle line:84%
and you can't see what
you're doing on the ground.

00:37:23.190 --> 00:37:25.720 align:middle line:84%
And I thought that was
a legitimate point.

00:37:25.720 --> 00:37:28.320 align:middle line:84%
Yes, OK, let's see
what could be done.

00:37:28.320 --> 00:37:30.710 align:middle line:84%
And people assured
me, oh, you would

00:37:30.710 --> 00:37:33.817 align:middle line:84%
have to have surveying equipment
or modern angle measurements.

00:37:33.817 --> 00:37:34.900 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I don't think so.

00:37:34.900 --> 00:37:37.747 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Or you would have
to use something or other.

00:37:37.747 --> 00:37:39.830 align:middle line:84%
Some people thought maybe
they used a grid method.

00:37:39.830 --> 00:37:44.670 align:middle line:84%
Well, I had done a lot of work
as a kid as a sign painter

00:37:44.670 --> 00:37:47.480 align:middle line:84%
and had painted billboards
on the sides of buildings

00:37:47.480 --> 00:37:50.880 align:middle line:84%
with giant pictures, and I
knew it wasn't done with a grid

00:37:50.880 --> 00:37:54.230 align:middle line:84%
system, because a grid system
would minimize errors to

00:37:54.230 --> 00:37:55.330 align:middle line:90%
within a square.

00:37:55.330 --> 00:37:59.130 align:middle line:84%
You would not have, for
example, gross asymmetry,

00:37:59.130 --> 00:38:02.300 align:middle line:84%
mismatched wings, for example,
or that kind of thing.

00:38:02.300 --> 00:38:04.430 align:middle line:84%
So I was sure they
didn't do that.

00:38:04.430 --> 00:38:09.110 align:middle line:84%
I simply got a notion that
I could take a small drawing

00:38:09.110 --> 00:38:12.930 align:middle line:84%
and mock it up to a big
drawing using a center

00:38:12.930 --> 00:38:14.709 align:middle line:90%
line and some reference points.

00:38:14.709 --> 00:38:16.250 align:middle line:84%
I won't go into
great detail with it,

00:38:16.250 --> 00:38:18.825 align:middle line:84%
but basically plotting
some dots and connecting

00:38:18.825 --> 00:38:22.610 align:middle line:84%
them, a very simple, no
measuring of angles, nothing.

00:38:22.610 --> 00:38:24.740 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They might have
done it with rope, too.

00:38:24.740 --> 00:38:26.031 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: Well, they may have.

00:38:26.031 --> 00:38:29.350 align:middle line:84%
They certainly probably
scribed their circles with rope

00:38:29.350 --> 00:38:32.020 align:middle line:90%
and made spirals using that.

00:38:32.020 --> 00:38:36.800 align:middle line:84%
So I decided that if I
made one, I couldn't get by

00:38:36.800 --> 00:38:38.630 align:middle line:90%
with just making a small one.

00:38:38.630 --> 00:38:40.660 align:middle line:84%
Because I could hear the
people say, oh, yeah,

00:38:40.660 --> 00:38:42.420 align:middle line:90%
sure, Nickell made a little one.

00:38:42.420 --> 00:38:48.200 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, he could make the giant
condor, which is 440 feet long.

00:38:48.200 --> 00:38:51.410 align:middle line:84%
And I thought, OK, I'll
make the giant condor.

00:38:51.410 --> 00:38:55.730 align:middle line:84%
I got a landfill area and some
assorted cousins and nephews,

00:38:55.730 --> 00:39:00.650 align:middle line:84%
and we drove a post and
marked off the 440 feet

00:39:00.650 --> 00:39:02.310 align:middle line:90%
for the giant condor.

00:39:02.310 --> 00:39:04.040 align:middle line:90%
And I honestly gulped.

00:39:04.040 --> 00:39:07.540 align:middle line:84%
As confident as I was, and
I was sure I could do this,

00:39:07.540 --> 00:39:11.040 align:middle line:84%
to see on the ground
how absolutely huge

00:39:11.040 --> 00:39:11.957 align:middle line:90%
this was going to be--

00:39:11.957 --> 00:39:12.756 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It is big.

00:39:12.756 --> 00:39:14.130 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: --was intimidating.

00:39:14.130 --> 00:39:18.130 align:middle line:84%
But we just proceeded, and in a
couple of days, we had done it,

00:39:18.130 --> 00:39:19.465 align:middle line:90%
reproduced the giant condor.

00:39:19.465 --> 00:39:21.090 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did you look
at it from above?

00:39:21.090 --> 00:39:23.130 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: We did later
fly over and film it.

00:39:23.130 --> 00:39:24.990 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Did it look like one?

00:39:24.990 --> 00:39:27.700 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Scientific American
magazine said that my copy was,

00:39:27.700 --> 00:39:31.160 align:middle line:84%
quote-- I memorized
this because I was so

00:39:31.160 --> 00:39:35.770 align:middle line:84%
flattered-- "remarkable in its
exactness to the original."

00:39:35.770 --> 00:39:40.000 align:middle line:84%
In fact, we were so
accurate in our method

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:44.420 align:middle line:84%
that in making a small drawing,
I had made one little error.

00:39:44.420 --> 00:39:47.470 align:middle line:84%
I had a line kind
of askew wrong.

00:39:47.470 --> 00:39:48.970 align:middle line:90%
And we copied that perfectly.

00:39:48.970 --> 00:39:51.480 align:middle line:84%
So you could see
that you can actually

00:39:51.480 --> 00:39:53.410 align:middle line:84%
pretty faithfully take
your small drawing

00:39:53.410 --> 00:39:55.640 align:middle line:90%
and make a big one.

00:39:55.640 --> 00:39:59.980 align:middle line:84%
I later decided that the
Nazcas probably didn't

00:39:59.980 --> 00:40:01.870 align:middle line:90%
plot as many points as I did.

00:40:01.870 --> 00:40:05.777 align:middle line:84%
And I thought I could do much
more freehand than I had done.

00:40:05.777 --> 00:40:06.985 align:middle line:90%
This is a little more daring.

00:40:06.985 --> 00:40:09.560 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, but there
is no doubt they made it.

00:40:09.560 --> 00:40:12.890 align:middle line:84%
The question is, did they
make it for the gods?

00:40:12.890 --> 00:40:15.690 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Well, this
is the big question.

00:40:15.690 --> 00:40:18.570 align:middle line:84%
But I came out of retirement
to-- "National Geographic"

00:40:18.570 --> 00:40:19.950 align:middle line:90%
wanted me to make one for them.

00:40:19.950 --> 00:40:23.040 align:middle line:84%
And I said, but I've done
that, been there, done that.

00:40:23.040 --> 00:40:25.149 align:middle line:84%
And they said, yes,
but you didn't film it.

00:40:25.149 --> 00:40:26.440 align:middle line:90%
I said, well, you got me there.

00:40:26.440 --> 00:40:27.080 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: This time you did.

00:40:27.080 --> 00:40:28.420 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: So I had to go
make one for them, made

00:40:28.420 --> 00:40:29.810 align:middle line:90%
the giant spider for them.

00:40:29.810 --> 00:40:32.650 align:middle line:84%
And they filmed it
from a cherry picker.

00:40:32.650 --> 00:40:33.780 align:middle line:90%
And it was great.

00:40:33.780 --> 00:40:37.500 align:middle line:84%
But what I've come
to-- at one point,

00:40:37.500 --> 00:40:41.580 align:middle line:84%
I noticed that the
Nazca drawings are all

00:40:41.580 --> 00:40:43.310 align:middle line:90%
done with a continuous line.

00:40:43.310 --> 00:40:45.440 align:middle line:84%
I'm not the first to
have noticed this.

00:40:45.440 --> 00:40:48.450 align:middle line:84%
But in other words,
on the Nazca pottery,

00:40:48.450 --> 00:40:51.970 align:middle line:84%
they would draw a body or a
wing, lift the brush or pen,

00:40:51.970 --> 00:40:56.164 align:middle line:84%
draw another feature, and it
was not done continuously.

00:40:56.164 --> 00:40:58.330 align:middle line:84%
But on the ground, it's a
whole different situation.

00:40:58.330 --> 00:41:02.660 align:middle line:84%
Once you start, you
make the entire figure

00:41:02.660 --> 00:41:06.360 align:middle line:84%
without lifting the
imaginary pencil.

00:41:06.360 --> 00:41:10.460 align:middle line:84%
And I thought when I first
started this, well, that's

00:41:10.460 --> 00:41:13.360 align:middle line:84%
just because they're plotting
points like I'm doing,

00:41:13.360 --> 00:41:15.030 align:middle line:84%
and they're just
connecting as they go,

00:41:15.030 --> 00:41:18.530 align:middle line:84%
which I think is a perfectly
reasonable hypothesis, just

00:41:18.530 --> 00:41:19.680 align:middle line:90%
completely reasonable.

00:41:19.680 --> 00:41:23.780 align:middle line:84%
I think it's wrong, but
it made perfect sense.

00:41:23.780 --> 00:41:28.180 align:middle line:84%
We now know-- and my friend Tony
Aveni from Colgate University

00:41:28.180 --> 00:41:30.215 align:middle line:90%
is a great Nazca expert.

00:41:30.215 --> 00:41:31.760 align:middle line:90%
He's done a lot of work on this.

00:41:31.760 --> 00:41:38.310 align:middle line:84%
And he calls these figures
labyrinths in the desert.

00:41:38.310 --> 00:41:41.070 align:middle line:84%
And what happens is
that each of the figures

00:41:41.070 --> 00:41:43.560 align:middle line:84%
has a couple of
extraneous lines,

00:41:43.560 --> 00:41:47.680 align:middle line:84%
like the monkey has
two lines going up

00:41:47.680 --> 00:41:50.120 align:middle line:84%
to the base of the
tail, or the spider

00:41:50.120 --> 00:41:53.950 align:middle line:84%
has two lines going off at a
right angle to the bottom leg.

00:41:53.950 --> 00:41:56.910 align:middle line:84%
And those lines serve
no layout purposes

00:41:56.910 --> 00:42:01.340 align:middle line:84%
or anatomical purposes, nothing,
except that if you combine

00:42:01.340 --> 00:42:03.650 align:middle line:84%
that with a
continuous line, what

00:42:03.650 --> 00:42:07.030 align:middle line:84%
you get is you walk
into one of those lines,

00:42:07.030 --> 00:42:09.080 align:middle line:84%
and on the ground--
I've been to Nazca--

00:42:09.080 --> 00:42:11.200 align:middle line:90%
they just look like footpaths.

00:42:11.200 --> 00:42:13.820 align:middle line:84%
They've been made
by clearing gravel

00:42:13.820 --> 00:42:17.120 align:middle line:84%
so that where the line
is, the gravel is removed,

00:42:17.120 --> 00:42:20.020 align:middle line:84%
and the rest has still got
the dark gravel on the ground.

00:42:20.020 --> 00:42:22.120 align:middle line:90%
So they look like footpaths.

00:42:22.120 --> 00:42:24.580 align:middle line:84%
If you walk in one of
the extraneous lines,

00:42:24.580 --> 00:42:27.130 align:middle line:84%
you will then continue to
walk the entire figure.

00:42:27.130 --> 00:42:29.160 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of them
have extra lines

00:42:29.160 --> 00:42:30.760 align:middle line:90%
and a lot of winding about.

00:42:30.760 --> 00:42:32.510 align:middle line:84%
But you will come back
out the other line.

00:42:32.510 --> 00:42:34.135 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It is
remarkable architecture.

00:42:34.135 --> 00:42:36.590 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: And I think
that these are probably,

00:42:36.590 --> 00:42:42.040 align:middle line:84%
and so does Aveni-- we think
they're ritual walking paths,

00:42:42.040 --> 00:42:45.480 align:middle line:84%
not necessarily meant to be
seen by the gods in the sky.

00:42:45.480 --> 00:42:47.700 align:middle line:84%
That may not have
been the main motive.

00:42:47.700 --> 00:42:51.020 align:middle line:84%
But they were certainly
processional, mystical

00:42:51.020 --> 00:42:54.450 align:middle line:84%
walking paths, perhaps
to gain the power

00:42:54.450 --> 00:43:00.160 align:middle line:84%
of that particular condor or
spider, sort of like a totem.

00:43:00.160 --> 00:43:01.980 align:middle line:90%
But we're guessing on that.

00:43:01.980 --> 00:43:05.020 align:middle line:84%
But if I'm sure
of very much, I'm

00:43:05.020 --> 00:43:09.120 align:middle line:84%
pretty sure that those
were ritual walking paths.

00:43:09.120 --> 00:43:11.940 align:middle line:84%
And I think they're
amazing, and I

00:43:11.940 --> 00:43:16.630 align:middle line:84%
think we don't need von Daniken
to take their wonderful work

00:43:16.630 --> 00:43:19.540 align:middle line:84%
away from them and attribute
it to extraterrestrials.

00:43:19.540 --> 00:43:20.840 align:middle line:90%
I'm offended by it.

00:43:20.840 --> 00:43:25.990 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Final question--
is there a God?

00:43:25.990 --> 00:43:28.120 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: We don't know.

00:43:28.120 --> 00:43:30.500 align:middle line:84%
I assume there is
not, because there

00:43:30.500 --> 00:43:35.360 align:middle line:84%
is nothing-- there is no
need to postulate a God.

00:43:35.360 --> 00:43:41.490 align:middle line:84%
Once you know that evolution
is a reality, you could say,

00:43:41.490 --> 00:43:43.150 align:middle line:84%
well, God created
man, but you have

00:43:43.150 --> 00:43:46.880 align:middle line:84%
to say, yeah, first what he did
was he created the dinosaurs.

00:43:46.880 --> 00:43:49.920 align:middle line:84%
And then He looked down and He
said, oh, my goodness, those

00:43:49.920 --> 00:43:53.380 align:middle line:84%
gigantic, lumbering beasts
with the little brains-- what

00:43:53.380 --> 00:43:54.650 align:middle line:90%
was I thinking?

00:43:54.650 --> 00:43:57.049 align:middle line:84%
I'll do better next--
I'll create man,

00:43:57.049 --> 00:43:58.590 align:middle line:84%
but I'm not going
to do it like that.

00:43:58.590 --> 00:44:01.772 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to have
him evolve slowly.

00:44:01.772 --> 00:44:03.230 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if that
makes sense to you,

00:44:03.230 --> 00:44:06.120 align:middle line:90%
by all means get out your Bible.

00:44:06.120 --> 00:44:09.020 align:middle line:90%
But it doesn't make sense to me.

00:44:09.020 --> 00:44:13.250 align:middle line:84%
And I don't think we need to
postulate a deity in order

00:44:13.250 --> 00:44:15.350 align:middle line:90%
to explain things.

00:44:15.350 --> 00:44:17.540 align:middle line:84%
I think there always
was something.

00:44:17.540 --> 00:44:18.880 align:middle line:90%
There never was nothing.

00:44:18.880 --> 00:44:21.890 align:middle line:84%
I think nothingness is
an utter impossibility.

00:44:21.890 --> 00:44:24.380 align:middle line:84%
There never was nothing and
then something came out of it.

00:44:24.380 --> 00:44:25.529 align:middle line:90%
I may be wrong.

00:44:25.529 --> 00:44:27.570 align:middle line:84%
Physicists are divided
over some of these issues.

00:44:27.570 --> 00:44:29.220 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How did
it start, though?

00:44:29.220 --> 00:44:31.719 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I would agree with
you that there wasn't nothing.

00:44:31.719 --> 00:44:33.760 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: It didn't start,
is what I'm thinking.

00:44:33.760 --> 00:44:34.230 align:middle line:90%
There always--

00:44:34.230 --> 00:44:35.560 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We'll never
get the answer.

00:44:35.560 --> 00:44:37.310 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: There
always was something.

00:44:37.310 --> 00:44:41.010 align:middle line:84%
And the Big Bang was
just one more event.

00:44:41.010 --> 00:44:41.940 align:middle line:90%
And before that was--

00:44:41.940 --> 00:44:43.810 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Something blew
up that was already here.

00:44:43.810 --> 00:44:45.910 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Something
before that and before that

00:44:45.910 --> 00:44:46.500 align:middle line:90%
and before that.

00:44:46.500 --> 00:44:47.510 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We'll never
get the answer, Joe.

00:44:47.510 --> 00:44:49.310 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Well, maybe
not, but we're certainly--

00:44:49.310 --> 00:44:49.630 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I don't think so.

00:44:49.630 --> 00:44:51.850 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: The more
we study our world,

00:44:51.850 --> 00:44:55.940 align:middle line:84%
the more-- for example, if we
had said what you just said,

00:44:55.940 --> 00:44:59.610 align:middle line:84%
we won't ever know, if we had
said that long before Darwin,

00:44:59.610 --> 00:45:02.020 align:middle line:84%
and people did, they
weren't on a track

00:45:02.020 --> 00:45:03.950 align:middle line:90%
to know as much as we know now.

00:45:03.950 --> 00:45:06.660 align:middle line:84%
But Darwin dared to
look for answers.

00:45:06.660 --> 00:45:08.780 align:middle line:90%
And we know so much more now.

00:45:08.780 --> 00:45:11.280 align:middle line:90%
We know that we evolved.

00:45:11.280 --> 00:45:14.360 align:middle line:84%
Back to Galileo, we know we're
not the center of the universe.

00:45:14.360 --> 00:45:16.515 align:middle line:90%
We are learning constantly.

00:45:16.515 --> 00:45:18.640 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We know there are
other planets out there.

00:45:18.640 --> 00:45:21.970 align:middle line:84%
>>NICKELL: Exactly,
and other galaxies.

00:45:21.970 --> 00:45:23.520 align:middle line:90%
And it's wonderful.

00:45:23.520 --> 00:45:28.480 align:middle line:84%
But yes, we will
never, ever know

00:45:28.480 --> 00:45:29.860 align:middle line:90%
everything that's out there.

00:45:29.860 --> 00:45:33.710 align:middle line:10%
But we are learning much,
much more about ourselves

00:45:33.710 --> 00:45:37.790 align:middle line:10%
and our world, and
science is doing that.

00:45:37.790 --> 00:45:41.647 align:middle line:84%
And I hope to have played a
little, small role in that.

00:45:41.647 --> 00:45:43.730 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Joe, thanks for
being on "Beyond Belief,"

00:45:43.730 --> 00:45:44.780 align:middle line:90%
I appreciate it.

00:45:44.780 --> 00:45:45.870 align:middle line:90%
>>NICKELL: My pleasure.

00:45:45.870 --> 00:45:48.360 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: OK, so you just
heard it from a skeptic.

00:45:48.360 --> 00:45:53.820 align:middle line:10%
He doesn't believe in
ghosts-- not yet, anyway.

00:45:53.820 --> 00:45:55.020 align:middle line:10%
Not yet.

00:45:55.020 --> 00:45:55.880 align:middle line:10%
I'm George Noory.

00:45:55.880 --> 00:45:57.630 align:middle line:84%
Thanks for watching
"Beyond Belief."

00:45:57.630 --> 00:46:02.480 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:46:02.480 --> 00:46:04.778 align:middle line:90%